# GitHub workflow

## Branches

- **Always create a branch** for any feature, fix, or test task. One per logical unit of work like the PR. Never commit directly to `main`.
- **Naming:** `<tool-or-harness>/<short-descriptor>` using kebab-case. **Tool or harness** is the primary system assisting with the branch (use a short, consistent lowercase slug): e.g. `cursor/…` (Cursor), `claude/…` (Claude Code), `codex/…`, or another you standardize for this repo. The **descriptor** must reflect the actual work, not the chat title (e.g. `cursor/bde-form-tests`, not `cursor/review-ad-campaign-abc123`).
- For work with no agent assist, `manual/…` is fine.

## Pull requests

- **Always open a PR** when a feature, fix, or test task is complete. Use the **GitHub CLI** (`gh`) — e.g. `gh pr create`.
- **OpenSpec `/opsx:apply`:** Commit/push/PR timing lives in the active schema’s `apply.instruction` (see `openspec/schemas/*/schema.yaml`) and `skills/openspec-apply-change.md` step 8 — not duplicated here.
- **One PR per logical unit of work.** Don't bundle unrelated changes.
- **Never merge or approve the PR.** User reviews CI checks and the Vercel preview, and always makes the final merge decision. Agents must not run `gh pr merge` or approve reviews.
- **Never have two PRs open for the same work item.** If a PR exists for the current task, push additional fixes to that branch rather than opening a new PR. Keep iterating on the existing PR until all checks pass.
- **PR description** must include: what changed and why. Don't include a test plan unless it's an actual automated test that's been implemented.
- **Founder intent section.** When the work belongs to an OpenSpec change with a Human anchor, quote one anchor line verbatim under a `## Founder intent` heading in the PR body. This keeps Katy's words in the durable GitHub record so project history ("tell-the-story"-style ledgers) can be derived from PRs instead of reconstructed by archaeology.
- **Embed proposed-design screenshots for UI changes.** When a change has a Figma proposed frame (see `rules/figma.mdc`), include the screenshot(s) **inline in the PR body**, not just a Figma link. Because Figma's screenshot URLs are short-lived and branch-relative URLs break when the branch is deleted on merge, commit the PNG into the change's assets (`openspec/changes/<id>/assets/proposed-*.png`) and reference it by **commit-SHA** raw URL so it survives merge: `![…](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<owner>/<repo>/<commit-sha>/openspec/changes/<id>/assets/<file>.png)`. Capture with the Figma MCP `get_screenshot` (curl the short-lived URL to the asset path), commit, then build the body against that commit's SHA.

### Single ready-for-review PR until merge (default)

- Prefer **one active branch + one PR** per ongoing effort. Keep **adding commits to that branch** and **updating the same PR** until user approves and merges. Avoid opening many parallel branches/PRs for follow-ups in the same workstream.
- Open PRs **ready for review, not draft**, so the automated Copilot review kicks off immediately (`gh pr create` without `--draft`). If a PR was opened as a draft, mark it ready (`gh pr ready`).
- Start a **new** branch + PR only after the previous one is merged, or when the work is **clearly unrelated** (different experiment, different product surface).
- Push additional commits to the same branch to refresh the existing PR.

### Copilot review loop

- After opening a PR (or pushing substantive new commits to one), **wait for Copilot's automated review** and check for its comments before ending the task — it usually posts within a few minutes (`gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/pulls/NUMBER/comments`).
- **Address every actionable comment**: push fixes to the same branch, then **reply to each comment** saying what changed — or why no change was needed. Never leave a Copilot comment unanswered.
- If a session finds an open PR with unanswered Copilot comments from an earlier session, address them the same way.
- The user still reviews and makes the final merge decision.

